The problem asks to show that if $n$ is odd, we can assign a starting endpoint (direction) for each frog such that no two frogs ever meet at an intersection. This can be achieved by ordering the lines by slope (or any other geometric ordering) and assigning the direction based on the parity of the line's rank in that order. The key geometric insight is that the sum of the indices of the intersection point of two lines $i$ and $j$ has the same parity as `rank(i) + rank(j) + 1`.

