The problem asks us to assign a direction to each of the $n$ segments (where $n$ is odd) so that frogs starting at the chosen endpoints and moving towards the other end never meet at an intersection point. This corresponds to assigning a boolean $\epsilon_i$ to each segment $i$ such that for every pair $i \ne j$, the time $t$ when frog $i$ reaches the intersection $X_{ij}$ is different from the time frog $j$ reaches it.

Let $r_{ij}$ be the rank of the intersection $X_{ij}$ on segment $i$ (ordered from start to end). If $\epsilon_i = \text{false}$, the frog moves in increasing order of ranks, reaching $X_{ij}$ at time $r_{ij}$. If $\epsilon_i = \text{true}$, the frog moves in decreasing order, reaching $X_{ij}$ at time $(n-2) - r_{ij}$.
Since $n$ is odd, $n-2$ is odd, so $r_{ij}$ and $(n-2) - r_{ij}$ have different parities. specifically, the arrival time modulo 2 is $r_{ij} + \epsilon_i \pmod 2$.
To avoid collisions, it suffices to ensure $r_{ij} + \epsilon_i \not\equiv r_{ji} + \epsilon_j \pmod 2$ for all $i \ne j$. This is equivalent to $\epsilon_i + \epsilon_j \equiv r_{ij} + r_{ji} + 1 \pmod 2$.

This system of linear equations over $\mathbb{Z}_2$ on the complete graph $K_n$ is consistent if and only if for every cycle (equivalently, every triangle), the sum of the RHS values is $0 \pmod 2$. For a triangle $ijk$, the sum is $(r_{ij} + r_{ji} + 1) + (r_{jk} + r_{kj} + 1) + (r_{ki} + r_{ik} + 1) \equiv \sum_{cyc} (r_{ij} + r_{ji}) + 1 \pmod 2$.
It is a known property of arrangements of pseudolines that for any three segments forming a triangle, the sum of relative ranks is odd (specifically, the number of lines crossing the boundary of the triangle is even, leading to the sum being $1 \pmod 2$). Thus the system is solvable.

We construct the solution by fixing $\epsilon_0 = 0$ and setting $\epsilon_i$ for $i > 0$ to satisfy the equation for the edge $(0, i)$. The consistency condition ensures that the equation for any other edge $(i, j)$ is also satisfied.

