Based on the geometric properties of the line arrangement, we construct a solution using the "Black on Left" strategy.
The arrangement of lines defines a 2-coloring of the regions. We assign a direction to each segment such that the region to the left of the frog at the start of its movement is "Black" (color 0).
The color of a point $P$ is determined by the parity of the number of lines separating $P$ from a reference "infinity" (equivalent to counting lines $k$ where $P$ is on the negative side).
For a segment $i$, the midpoint $M_i$ lies on line $i$ but not on any other line (generically). The color of the regions adjacent to $M_i$ depends on the other $n-1$ lines. Let $C_{-i}(M_i)$ be the parity of the count of lines $k \neq i$ such that $M_i$ is on the negative side of $k$.
If we orient $i$ as given ($P_i \to Q_i$), the "Left" side is the positive side of line $i$. Its color is $C_{-i}(M_i) \oplus 0$.
If we reverse $i$ ($Q_i \to P_i$), the "Left" side is the negative side of line $i$. Its color is $C_{-i}(M_i) \oplus 1$.
Since we want the Left region to be color 0 (Black), we choose the original direction if $C_{-i}(M_i)$ is even, and the reverse if $C_{-i}(M_i)$ is odd.
At any intersection point $X$ where frogs $f$ and $g$ meet at step $t$, the region to the left of $f$ and the region to the left of $g$ must have the same color $0 \oplus (t \pmod 2)$. However, these two regions are adjacent in the arrangement (separated by line $g$ for $f$, and line $f$ for $g$), so they must have different colors. This contradiction proves no collision is possible.

