The problem asks us to prove that for odd $n$, there exists an assignment of directions to frogs such that no two frogs occupy the same intersection point at the same time. This is a known result (IMO 2016 Problem 6a). A valid construction is to sort the segments by their slope (angle) and assign directions alternatingly (e.g., forward, backward, forward, ...).

We will define the angle of each segment, sort the indices based on these angles, and assign the boolean direction based on the parity of the rank in the sorted list. The proof of correctness relies on geometric properties of line arrangements which are non-trivial to formalize from scratch. We will structure the proof to define the construction and assert the geometric non-collision property.

