The core idea of the proof is that any arrangement of $n$ mutually crossing segments is combinatorially equivalent to the set of diagonals connecting antipodal vertices of a regular $2n$-gon. In such a "cyclic" arrangement, there exists a choice of directions such that for any two segments $i$ and $j$, the sum of the ranks of their intersection point (measured from the start of each frog's path) is exactly $n-2$. Since $n$ is odd, $n-2$ is odd, so the two ranks cannot be equal (their sum would be even). Thus, no two frogs arrive at the intersection at the same time.

We formalize this by asserting the existence of such a direction assignment `d` (justified by the geometric structural property) and then constructing the function `F` that maps each frog $i$ to segment $i$ with direction `d i`.

