The provided Lean code is for IMO 2016 Problem 6, part (a). The problem asks to prove that for an odd number of segments $n$, there exists an assignment of frogs and directions such that no two frogs collide.

The proof relies on a combinatorial property of line arrangements: for any arrangement of $n$ lines (segments) in general position, the lines can be ordered (e.g., by slope) such that for any two lines $L_i, L_j$ with indices $i, j$ in the ordering, the sum of the number of intersections on $L_i$ before $L_j$ and on $L_j$ before $L_i$ has the same parity as $i+j+1$. Using this property, we can assign directions based on the parity of the index: even-indexed lines move forward, odd-indexed lines move backward. This assignment ensures that for any pair of frogs, their positions at any time step differ either in parity or in value (due to the parity of the sum of ranks), preventing collisions.

