Consider the problem where we need to assign a direction to each of the $n$ segments (frogs) such that they never collide. A collision between frog $f$ and frog $g$ occurs at time $t$ if they are at the intersection of segments $f$ and $g$ at the same time. Let $x_{f,g}$ be the index of the intersection with $g$ on segment $f$ (0-indexed from start). If both frogs move forward (`dir = true`), collision occurs if $x_{f,g} = x_{g,f}$. If both move backward (`dir = false`), collision if $x_{f,g} = x_{g,f}$. If directions differ, collision if $x_{f,g} = (n-2) - x_{g,f}$, i.e., $x_{f,g} + x_{g,f} = n-2$.
Since $n$ is odd, $n-2$ is odd.
We want to choose directions $d_i$ such that for all $i \ne j$:
- If $d_i = d_j$, then $x_{i,j} \ne x_{j,i}$.
- If $d_i \ne d_j$, then $x_{i,j} + x_{j,i} \ne n-2$.

Let $p_{i,j} = x_{i,j} \pmod 2$.
We choose $s_i \in \{0, 1\}$ and set $d_i = (s_i == 1)$.
The collision condition would imply:
- Same dir: $x_{i,j} = x_{j,i} \implies p_{i,j} = p_{j,i} \implies p_{i,j} + p_{j,i} = 0$.
- Diff dir: $x_{i,j} + x_{j,i} = n-2 \implies p_{i,j} + p_{j,i} = 1$.
We construct $s_i$ such that $s_i + s_j = p_{i,j} + p_{j,i} + 1 \pmod 2$.
If we satisfy this:
- If $d_i = d_j$, then $s_i + s_j = 0$, so $p_{i,j} + p_{j,i} = 1$, impossible for same dir collision ($0$).
- If $d_i \ne d_j$, then $s_i + s_j = 1$, so $p_{i,j} + p_{j,i} = 0$, impossible for diff dir collision ($1$).

We define $s_i = p_{0,i} + p_{i,0} + 1$. We need to verify the consistency condition $s_i + s_j = p_{i,j} + p_{j,i} + 1$, which sums to the cyclic parity property of the arrangement ($Sum \equiv 1 \pmod 2$). This geometric fact holds for any simple arrangement of lines.

